One new finding emitted below: arbitrary-file open + shebang side-channel via the uncommitted `infer_lang_for_file`. Total: 20 findings.

---
record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 417,
  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "endpoint": "every /api/v1/runs that drives PayloadSynthesis or SpecDerivation against a hostile repo workspace",
  "rationale": "`infer_lang_for_file` opens `workspace_root.join(rel_path)` (ai_pipeline.rs:427) and reads the first 256 bytes with `std::fs::File::open` (:428) — no canonicalisation, no `starts_with(workspace_root)` confinement check, no `O_NOFOLLOW`, no symlink-metadata test. The function is called from `build_inputs` (:286 PayloadSynthesis pass) and `build_spec_inputs` (:676 SpecDerivation pass), each iterating every `FindingDiagnostic.path` the nyx static scanner emitted for a hostile-content repo. nyctos's threat model treats scanned repo content as adversarial (the whole point of the product is to find bugs in attacker-supplied code), so an attacker who controls a scanned repo gets two distinct primitives:\n\n(a) **Path::join absolute-overwrite read** — Rust's `Path::join` on Unix returns the second component verbatim when it is absolute (the documented `std::path::Path::join` semantics: 'If path is absolute, it replaces the current path'). The function's only filter before the read is `if basename.contains('.') { return from_ext; }` (:423) which gates on the LAST segment's dot. A path like `/etc/shadow` has basename `shadow` (no dot) → join discards the workspace root → `File::open(\"/etc/shadow\")` runs under the daemon UID. The 256-byte read is silent on the wire, but the *consequence* — daemon UID opens /etc/shadow, /root/.ssh/id_*, /proc/<pid>/environ for any other process owned by the same UID, /var/log/auth.log, etc. — is real: triggers auditd alarms (operationally visible noise), establishes proof-of-read for forensics, and the lang return value reflects whether the file started with `#!`-recognised interp (`python` / `javascript` / `typescript` / `ruby` / `php` / `perl` / `unknown` — a 3-bit oracle over content type). Reachable when a nyx static rule fires on a diagnostic that names a path-shaped string the rule constructed from the workspace's directory listing — any rule that emits an absolute path (some semgrep-style rules do; nyx's specific ruleset isn't visible from this crate but the *shape* — `path: String` with no normalisation — is the bug, not any particular rule's reachability).\n\n(b) **Symlink-follow workspace escape** — `std::fs::File::open` resolves symlinks unconditionally (Linux/macOS default). A hostile repo committed via git carries symlinks verbatim through clone (git transports symlinks; `git config core.symlinks` defaults to true on Unix). Repo layout: `bin/runner` (regular extensionless file with `#!/usr/bin/env python` and a one-line `eval(open('/dev/stdin').read())`-style sink to attract a static rule), plus `installer` (symlink → `../../../etc/shadow`). When nyx scans the workspace, the static rule fires on `bin/runner` but, crucially, also fires on `installer` if the rule is content-agnostic (e.g., 'extensionless file in repo root with read permission'). The diag.path string `installer` is then fed to `infer_lang_for_file(workspace_root, \"installer\")`. The join is workspace-local, but `File::open` follows the symlink and reads `/etc/shadow`'s first 256 bytes from disk. The lang return is `unknown` (shadow doesn't start with `#!`), but the OPEN happened: same noise/audit consequences as (a), plus the side-channel that the file *was openable* (vs the open-failed case which also returns `unknown`).\n\n(c) **3-bit content-classification covert channel over the AI request log** — the lang result flows into `PayloadSynthesisInput.lang` (and `SpecDerivationInput.lang`) and onward into the AI request body. AI requests are logged on the operator side (TraceLayer + AnthropicSdkAdapter's request tracker — see finding #4 for the URI-logging vector applied to the bearer token; the same logging surface captures every AI request body). An attacker who controls many files in a repo encodes content classification via shebang choice: each extensionless file with a chosen `#!/usr/bin/env <interp>` distinguishes 6 interpreters (python/javascript/typescript/ruby/php/perl) plus `unknown` — log2(7) ≈ 2.8 bits per file. With N hostile files per scan and a multi-scan history, a slow covert channel exfiltrates host filesystem content classification via the AI request log without ever placing the bytes in an AI prompt directly. Distinct from finding #4 (which leaks the daemon's bearer to logs by misuse-pattern) and from finding #20 nothing — this is novel.\n\nStatic pass missed it because (i) `std::fs::File::open` is a *workspace-local trusted source* by every dataflow rule (the workspace path itself is operator-trusted), so taint analysis treats the open as a sink-into-trusted-storage, not a sink-into-attacker-influence; (ii) the dangerous behavior is the absence of three orthogonal hardenings (canonicalize + starts_with check; symlink_metadata + reject; OPEN with O_NOFOLLOW) — there is no tainted-flow sink to anchor on, the bug is in what's *not* there; (iii) the `if basename.contains('.')` gate looks like a path-shape filter, but is actually a *language-extension* shortcut and provides zero traversal protection.\n\nMitigations (orthogonal, pick at least two): (1) canonicalize both `workspace_root` and the join result and reject when the canonicalised join does not `starts_with(canonicalized_workspace_root)`; (2) `std::fs::symlink_metadata(&abs)?` and refuse to open when `metadata.file_type().is_symlink()`; (3) open with `OpenOptions::new().read(true).custom_flags(libc::O_NOFOLLOW)` on Unix so the kernel refuses to traverse the symlink even if the workspace check is bypassed; (4) reject `rel_path` at function entry when `Path::new(rel_path).is_absolute() || rel_path.split('/').any(|seg| seg == \"..\")`. The fix is tiny — the absence is what's exploitable.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Hostile repo recipe: `mkdir bin && printf '#!/usr/bin/env python\\nimport os\\nos.system(input())\\n' > bin/runner && chmod +x bin/runner && ln -s /etc/shadow installer && git add -A && git commit -m 'init' && git push`. Operator adds the repo via POST /api/v1/projects/:p/repos and triggers a scan. Verifier-side observation: daemon's `auditctl -w /etc/shadow -p r -k nyctos-read` log captures the read; AI request body (POST https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages, logged by AnthropicSdkAdapter request tracker) contains `\"lang\":\"unknown\"` for path `installer` (would have been `python` if the symlink pointed to a python file). For the Path::join absolute-overwrite primitive: craft a static rule that fires on diagnostic path `/etc/shadow` (achievable if the hostile repo plants a config file the scanner walks that contains an absolute-path string the rule interpolates into diag.path); same end state."
}

