record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos/src/ai_pipeline.rs",
  "line": 2675,
  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "endpoint": "<state>/traces/<run_id>/<task_id>.jsonl (audit log writer)",
  "rationale": "`write_exploration_audit_jsonl` builds the artefact path with two unchecked `Path::join`s: `traces_dir.join(run_id)` then `run_dir.join(format!(\"{task_id}.jsonl\"))` (ai_pipeline.rs:2675-2677). Neither component is normalised, validated, or confined. `task_id` is derived as `format!(\"expl-{repo}\")` in `build_exploration_scope` (ai_pipeline.rs:2505) where `repo` is the bundle's `RepoOutcome.repo` — a string the operator supplies when adding a repo to the project (POST /api/v1/projects/:p/repos surface). A repo id of `../../etc/cron.d/nyctos-pwn` produces `task_id = \"expl-../../etc/cron.d/nyctos-pwn\"` and the writer happily punches the JSONL file *outside* the traces tree under the daemon UID, with `truncate(true)` annihilating whatever was there. `run_id` is similar: an operator-influenced run identifier (UUID by default in the happy path, but no audit-side check enforces that shape — only the `runs.id` PK column type does, and SQLite TEXT accepts arbitrary bytes including `..`). A run id like `../../var/spool/cron/crontabs/root` lands the JSONL inside the cron spool. Three orthogonal absences make this stick: (i) no `Path::new(run_id).components().all(|c| matches!(c, Component::Normal(_)))` validation; (ii) no canonicalize-then-`starts_with(traces_dir)` confinement; (iii) no `O_NOFOLLOW` on the open, so even a benign id pointed at a pre-staged symlink redirects the write. Static pass missed it because the writer's source taint analysis would mark `run_id`/`task_id` as 'internal scan-bundle strings, operator-trusted'; the bug is the *absence* of three checks, not a tainted-flow sink. Fix: validate both components are single `Component::Normal` segments and reject anything else at function entry; `create_dir_all` + canonicalize + `starts_with` confinement on the final path; open with `OpenOptions::new().write(true).create_new(true)` (forces failure on existing symlink/file) or at minimum `custom_flags(libc::O_NOFOLLOW | libc::O_CLOEXEC)` on Unix.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Operator (or attacker with operator credentials reaching the repo-add endpoint) submits a project repo with id `../../../tmp/pwn`. Trigger a scan; observe a file appears at `<state>/traces/<run_id>/../../../tmp/pwn/expl-...jsonl` — i.e. `/tmp/pwn/expl-...jsonl` — owned by the daemon UID with operator-controlled JSONL content. Pivot: aim run_id or task_id at `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` (writer truncates) or a cron spool path (writer produces a syntactically-loose JSONL line that crond happily ignores until the attacker bundles a single line that crond parses as a job entry). Verifier seed: spawn the pass with `bundle.run_id = \"../../tmp/audit-escape\"` and assert `std::path::Path::new(\"/tmp/audit-escape/expl-foo.jsonl\").exists()` post-run."
}

