{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1376,
  "cap": "CROSS_RUN_REPO_LEAK",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/runs/{run_id}/findings (Closed-row injection path)",
  "rationale": "`findings_for_run` (router.rs:1302) builds the current-row set with a `FindingFilter { run_id: Some(&run_id), repo: q.repo.as_deref(), .. }` (router.rs:1316-1327) — DB-side, the run_id binds the projection. The Closed-row injection branch (router.rs:1362-1388) then iterates `prior_membership` and, for each finding-id NOT in the current set, calls `s.store.findings().get(fid)` (router.rs:1377). `FindingStore::get` (finding.rs:272) selects by primary key only — no run_id check, no repo check, no project check. The fetched `FindingRecord` is then passed to `row_passes_filter` (router.rs:1425-1465) which mirrors the `FindingFilter` facets, BUT crucially `row_passes_filter` only filters on `q.repo` when the caller passed `?repo=X`; an unfacted request (`GET /runs/{run_id}/findings`) skips the `record.repo != repo` guard entirely (router.rs:1429-1433). Combined with `RunStore::prior_run_id` (run.rs:171-186), which selects the chronologically-prior run with `WHERE started_at < ? AND id != ?` and ORDER BY `started_at DESC LIMIT 1` — NO repo / project_id scope — the prior run handed to the classifier may belong to an entirely different project than the current run. Concrete failure: operator A scans project-tenant-A (repo `customer-a/secret-app`); operator B then scans project-tenant-B (repo `customer-b/their-app`); a request to `GET /api/v1/runs/{tenant-B-run-id}/findings` (no `?repo=` facet) walks tenant-B's prior_run = tenant-A-run, lists tenant-A's `run_findings`, and for every finding-id NOT also present in tenant-B's current rows, fetches `findings.get(fid)` and surfaces tenant-A's repo / path / cap / rationale under `diff_status: \"closed\"`. The bearer token gates ARE in place, but in nyctos's threat model the single shared bearer authorises every project under one daemon — there is no per-project ACL. The intended invariant 'run X's findings endpoint surfaces only run X's findings' is broken by the Closed branch; the existing test `runs_findings_endpoint_applies_facet_filter_to_closed_rows` (api.rs:573-600) ONLY covers the case where `?repo=X` is supplied, not the unfacted base case. Three secondary breaks compound: (i) `record.run_id` in the surfaced `FindingWithDiff` body is the *latest* upserted run_id (because `findings.run_id` collapses on upsert per ON CONFLICT clause at finding.rs:198-211), which may be neither the queried run nor the prior run — a forensic auditor reading the response sees a `run_id` field that does not match the path parameter; (ii) `row_passes_filter` ALSO skips `repo` filtering when q.repo is None, so the test asymmetry is structural not just a coverage gap; (iii) the `status` facet in `row_passes_filter` (router.rs:1444-1448) filters on the COLLAPSED `record.status` not the prior-run status from `prior_membership`, so even with `?status=Closed` a caller cannot reliably enumerate diff-status=Closed rows — a UI that uses `?status=Closed` to fetch closed-since-prior will instead get rows whose CURRENT row body happens to be `status='Closed'`, missing the actual Closed-via-diff rows whose body is still `status='Open'`. Static pass missed it because the Closed branch is a NEW code path added in this diff, the bug is the absence of a run_id / repo guard on `findings.get(fid)`, and taint analysis sees no tainted source-to-sink flow (the fid loop variable comes from the database, not from operator input). Fix (any one closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) extend `findings.get(fid)` call site to assert `record.repo == current_run.repo` and `record.project_id == current_run.project_id` before pushing; (2) scope `prior_run_id` to the same `project_id` (or `repo`) as the current run — change run.rs:171 to `SELECT id FROM runs WHERE started_at < ? AND id != ? AND project_id = ? ORDER BY started_at DESC LIMIT 1`; (3) add a `repo` filter to `row_passes_filter` that defaults to `current_run.repo` even when `q.repo` is None, so the base case enforces same-repo invariant; (4) add a test mirroring `runs_findings_endpoint_applies_facet_filter_to_closed_rows` that does NOT pass `?repo=`, asserting `items` for run X never includes a row whose `repo != run_X.repo`.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Black-box: seed two runs into the store via the test harness (`sample_run(\"run-tenant-a\")` started_at=1000, `sample_run(\"run-tenant-b\")` started_at=5000); upsert one finding under run-tenant-a with `repo=\"tenant-a-secret-app\"`; do NOT upsert any finding under run-tenant-b; `GET /api/v1/runs/run-tenant-b/findings` (no facet). Expected: empty items array. Currently: items contains tenant-a's finding with `diff_status=\"closed\"` and `repo=\"tenant-a-secret-app\"`. Verifier-side regression test: `runs_findings_endpoint_does_not_leak_closed_rows_across_repos` — copy the existing test at api.rs:573 but omit `?repo=repo-1`; assert items.is_empty()."
}

