record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1399,
  "cap": "DIFF_STATUS_MISLABEL",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/runs/{run_id}/findings (classify_current_row Unchanged/Regressed branch)",
  "rationale": "`classify_current_row` compares `prior_status` (from `prior_membership`, sourced from the per-run `run_findings.status` snapshot — the prior run's actual observation) against `record.status` (from `FindingRecord`, sourced from the COLLAPSED `findings.status` row which `FindingStore::upsert` rewrites on EVERY observation via `ON CONFLICT(id) DO UPDATE SET ... status = excluded.status` at finding.rs:198-211). The intent of the function is to compare prior-run state against current-run state; the implementation compares prior-run state against the LATEST GLOBAL state. Two failure shapes drop out:\n\n(a) **future upsert silently flips the historical diff_status** — an attacker (or any later legitimate scan) who re-observes finding-id F under a fresh run Z with status `Closed` overwrites `findings.status` to `Closed`. A query `GET /runs/X/findings` (where X is an older run that observed F as Open) now sees `prior_membership[F] = Open` (the actual prior X-of-X observation), `record.status = Closed` (the LATEST global state, not what F was during X). The classifier reports `Regressed` even though the comparison is meaningless across-run. Symmetric reverse: future upsert flips F back to `Open`, the classifier reports `Unchanged` even when the current-run snapshot for X should still read F as Open at observation time and the prior was Closed.\n\n(b) **status update under the current run after the diff query is built races** — within a single run, the same finding-id can be upserted multiple times (e.g. an initial observation with status=Open, then a verifier-side `set_verify_result` flipping to Verified, then a triage UI write flipping to InTriage). Each upsert in `FindingStore::upsert` mirrors the new status into `run_findings(current_run, fid)` (finding.rs:240-249) AND collapses `findings.status` to the same value (finding.rs:198-211). The `list_filtered` query at router.rs:1328 reads `findings.status`; `list_run_membership` at router.rs:1334 reads `run_findings.status`. Both reads come from the same SqlitePool but are issued as separate queries, so a mid-flight `set_verify_result` (not in the upsert path but at `FindingStore::set_verify_result`, finding.rs:454, which does NOT touch run_findings at all per the visible diff!) updates `findings.status` without touching `run_findings.status` — so even WITHIN the current run, the comparison can read a stale run_findings.status against a fresh findings.status. `set_verify_result` is called once per verifier dispatch from ai_pipeline.rs:2271-2299 (per the existing finding #28's context) and is the ONLY mutator that flips status post-discovery; it is the path most likely to be active concurrently with a diff-query.\n\n(c) **classifier never reads the current run's run_findings row** — the whole point of the new join table is to record the (run_id, finding_id) snapshot. The current-run reading still goes through `findings.status` (the collapse), so for the *current* run the snapshot is whatever the latest cross-run upsert wrote. The fix would be to either join `run_findings(current_run)` into `list_filtered` to source the current-run status from the join, OR to read `record.status` from `current_membership.get(&record.id)` (mirroring the prior side).\n\nDistinct from finding #29 (cross-run/repo leak in the Closed branch) and #31 isn't about the Closed branch at all — it targets the Unchanged/Regressed comparison in `classify_current_row`. Distinct from finding #30 (DoS) which is about throughput. Static pass missed it because: (i) the bug is a *semantic mismatch* between two columns that look interchangeable (`run_findings.status` vs `findings.status`) and a static analyser has no concept of 'the latter is collapsed across runs and the former is per-run' — that knowledge lives in the migration comment, not in any type or constraint; (ii) there is no tainted source-to-sink flow; the bug is in a pure compare that reads from two structurally compatible string columns; (iii) the unit test `runs_findings_endpoint_marks_regressed_when_status_differs_from_prior` (api.rs:435-470) seeds a current-run upsert that mirrors what `findings.status` reports, so the test passes by coincidence — the test does NOT exercise a third later run that overwrites findings.status, nor a mid-flight `set_verify_result` that touches findings without touching run_findings. Fix (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) join the current-run membership in `findings_for_run` — issue a second `list_run_membership(&run_id)` call, source the comparison's `current_status` from that map rather than from `record.status`, eliminating the cross-run collapse from the comparison; (2) extend `FindingStore::set_verify_result` (and `manual_promote` / `manual_dismiss`) to ALSO write through to `run_findings(current_run, fid)` — those callers know the run_id from the surrounding context; otherwise the per-run snapshot drifts from the collapsed status; (3) add a regression test: seed run-A with F=Open, run-B with F=Open (no diff), run-C (current) with no observation of F → assert diff_status for the F surfaced under run-C's response is `Closed` (not `Unchanged` or `Regressed`); ALSO: seed run-A with F=Open, run-B with F=Open (current = B), then upsert F under a NEW run-Z with status=Closed — re-query `GET /runs/B/findings` and assert F surfaces as `Unchanged` (B's actual observation matched A's), not `Regressed` (which is what the current code does because record.status now reads Z's Closed); (4) consider deprecating `findings.status` as a meaningful column once `run_findings` is the source of truth — surface a 'latest known status' view via `MAX(observation_ts)` over the join rather than via the collapsed column.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: extend the existing test `runs_findings_endpoint_marks_unchanged_when_status_matches_prior` (api.rs:472-497) by adding a third run after the two existing ones — `let mut later = sample_run(\"run-later\"); later.started_at = 9_000; srv.store.runs().insert(&later).await.expect(\"later\"); let mut later_obs = sample_finding(\"run-later\", \"repo-1\", \"src/a.rs\", \"rule-1\"); later_obs.status = \"Closed\".to_string(); srv.store.findings().upsert(&later_obs).await.expect(\"later obs\");` — then re-issue `GET /api/v1/runs/run-current/findings` and assert items[0].diff_status is STILL `unchanged` (the legitimate snapshot comparison: prior=Open, current-observed=Open). Currently fails because `record.status` now reads `Closed` (the run-later collapse) and the classifier compares prior=Open vs record=Closed → `regressed`. Real-world trigger: any second scan against the same codebase that re-observes an existing finding silently rewrites the diff_status badge surfaced for every PRIOR run's findings view — a defender investigating a months-old run's regression chip cannot trust the badge, and the API's `prior_run_id` walk does not propagate the time-anchored comparison forward."
}

