record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-api/src/router.rs",
  "line": 1735,
  "cap": "PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY",
  "endpoint": "POST /api/v1/quarantine/:id/promote (manual candidate→finding promotion)",
  "rationale": "`promote_candidate_to_finding` (router.rs:1692-1738) writes a fresh `FindingRecord` whose `id` is `finding_id_hash(repo, path, line, cap, rule)` — a BLAKE3-hex string that does NOT start with `cand-` and shares no bytes with the source candidate's id. The function (a) does not copy the candidate's `trace_id` onto any field of the new finding (FindingRecord has no `trace_id` column anywhere in the schema — confirmed by grepping nyctos-core/src/store/finding.rs), (b) does not UPDATE `agent_traces.finding_id` to point the original NovelFindings trace at the new finding, and (c) only mutates `candidate_findings.status` to `Promoted` (router.rs:1736) — the candidate row keeps its `trace_id` back-link but the row itself is no longer surfaced anywhere in the operator UI's main findings/quarantine views (Promoted candidates are filtered out by the Pending-only query at candidate.rs:97-108 and by the quarantine_list endpoint logic). Net effect: the promoted finding's URL `/findings/<hex>/traces` routes through the else branch of the new dispatcher at router.rs:1838 → `list_for_finding(<hex>)` → SELECT FROM agent_traces WHERE finding_id = ?, which returns ZERO rows (the NovelFindings trace was inserted with finding_id = NULL per the migration's comment: 'candidate-backed traces leave finding_id NULL and get reached via the new join'). The trace viewer therefore shows an empty list for an AI-proposed-then-manually-promoted finding — *exactly* the case where an operator most wants to inspect the proposing AI call (to validate the Manual-Promote decision against the AI's rationale, payload hint, and conversation_jsonl_path). The candidate-side URL `/findings/<cand-id>/traces` still works, but no UI surface exposes the candidate id after promotion (the quarantine list filters Promoted out, the finding detail page only knows the new findings.id, and `verdict_blob` carries the original candidate id as a JSON field but is not surfaced as a clickable trace link). Three orthogonal absences make this stick: (i) `FindingRecord` schema has no column to carry forward the proposing trace_id — `attack_provenance: Some('ManualPromote')` and `verdict_blob` (carrying a serialised JSON with `candidate_id` but no trace pointer) are the only provenance the promote path stamps; (ii) the promote handler does not run an `UPDATE agent_traces SET finding_id = ? WHERE id = ?` to forward the link; (iii) `list_for_finding` does not transitively walk through `candidate_findings.trace_id` (it would need a UNION over the direct `agent_traces.finding_id = ?` index AND a JOIN through any promoted-candidate row whose source candidate had trace_id stamped — neither path exists). Distinct from #28 (apply_chain_outcome non-transactional partial writes — different writer, different table) and #29 (PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY on COALESCE asymmetry — different writer, payload/spec side, not novel-discovery promote side). Static pass missed it because the bug is the absence of a writer (no UPDATE on agent_traces, no carry-forward field) — there is no tainted-flow sink to anchor on and no schema constraint that would have flagged the missing link; the migration 0005 *introduces* the back-link but does not extend `findings` to carry the same link, so promotion silently severs the chain. Forensic consequence: an operator auditing a manually-promoted High-severity finding cannot reach the proposing AI call from the standard trace-viewer surface; combined with #19 (doctor secret-length oracle) and #4 (bearer in URL logs), an attacker who learns the candidate id (via any prior reconnaissance — leaked logs, the quarantine pre-promote UI screenshot, a /api/v1/quarantine response captured earlier) can still reach the trace via the `cand-` URL, while the legitimate operator viewing the post-promote UI sees an empty trace list and may falsely conclude 'no AI involvement'. Fix (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) extend `FindingRecord` (and the `findings` table via a new migration) with `trace_id TEXT REFERENCES agent_traces(id) ON DELETE SET NULL`; populate from `cand.trace_id` in `promote_candidate_to_finding` at router.rs:1731 alongside `prompt_version`; (2) in the same promote handler, issue `UPDATE agent_traces SET finding_id = ? WHERE id = ?` with the new finding's id when `cand.trace_id` is Some — surfaces the trace via the existing `list_for_finding` index without schema churn (but loses the candidate back-link, so prefer (1)); (3) extend `traces_for_finding` (router.rs:1828) to also UNION traces reached transitively via `candidate_findings WHERE promoted_finding_id = ?` (requires a new column on candidate_findings tracking the promotion target — or carry the inverse: store `promoted_to_finding_id` on the candidate row at promotion time so the trace viewer can walk candidate→trace by either direction); (4) at minimum, surface the candidate id in the FindingDetail UI (via verdict_blob's already-stamped `candidate_id` JSON field) as a clickable secondary link to `/findings/<cand-id>/traces` so the operator has a manual escape hatch until the schema fix lands.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: extend the existing test at ai_pipeline.rs:4096-4111 — after asserting `traces.len() == 1` for the candidate, manually promote the candidate via `nyctos_api::router::promote_candidate_to_finding(&server_state, &row).await.unwrap()` and then query `agent_traces().list_for_finding(&promoted_id).await` where `promoted_id = finding_id_hash(&row.repo, &row.path, row.line, &row.cap, &row.rule_hint.unwrap_or(format!('ai-exploration:{}', row.cap)))`; assert `traces.len() == 1` and `traces[0].id == cand.trace_id` — currently fails (returns empty). Real-world trigger: operator triages a Pending candidate via the quarantine UI, clicks Promote; clicks the resulting finding row; clicks 'View AI trace' (or hits `/api/v1/findings/<promoted-id>/traces` directly); receives `[]`. The original NovelFindings agent_traces row is orphaned from the operator's UI even though it persists in the database, and the candidate-side URL is no longer reachable through any UI navigation chain."
}

