record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/src/store/trace.rs",
  "line": 184,
  "cap": "SCOPE_INVARIANT_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "GET /api/v1/findings/cand-:id/traces (candidate-branch dispatcher)",
  "rationale": "`list_for_candidate` (trace.rs:163-193) executes `SELECT t.* FROM agent_traces t JOIN candidate_findings c ON c.trace_id = t.id WHERE c.id = ?` — no `AND t.task_kind = 'NovelFindings'` filter, no allowlist of task_kind values. The migration's doc comment at 0005_candidate_trace_id.sql:3-15 documents the intent explicitly: 'NovelFindingDiscovery writes one agent_traces row per batch and N candidate_findings rows for the candidates that batch produced. ... Trace rows still carry finding_id for the static-pass paths (PayloadSynthesis / SpecDerivation / ChainReasoning) where the trace is per-finding; candidate-backed traces leave finding_id NULL and get reached via the new join.' The schema and query do NOT bind that contract. Today the only writer (`apply_novel_outcome`, ai_pipeline.rs:1593-1620) is correct: it stamps `trace_id = NovelFindings trace.id` on each candidate. But the surface widens with every future writer. Three forward-compatibility primitives drop out: (a) **scope-of-trace-disclosure widens silently** — if a future PayloadSynthesis or ChainReasoning writer stamps `trace_id` on a candidate (e.g. for per-candidate verifier replay traces, or for chain-membership traces that are per-candidate not per-finding), the existing `/findings/cand-:id/traces` endpoint silently surfaces that trace's `verifier_blob` and `conversation_jsonl_path` (both columns are SELECTed verbatim in the JOIN at trace.rs:170-182). `verifier_blob` carries dynamic-validation hints (which payloads succeeded, the verifier's confirmed/not-confirmed verdict, replay_stable flags from finding #20 context) — exactly the signal an attacker who acquired the bearer (via #4 URL-token logging, #19 doctor secret-length oracle) wants. `conversation_jsonl_path` is a filesystem path to the raw AI prompt/response stream — combined with #21 (path traversal in audit-log writer) and #22 (symlink-follow), a leak of this path reveals where the audit JSONL lives. (b) **breaks the migration's documented contract** — `agent_traces` has no schema-side `task_kind` constraint that pins which kinds may be back-linked from candidates. A reviewer reading the migration assumes the contract holds; a writer landing two PRs later may not consult the migration before stamping. The invariant is purely social. (c) **interacts with #33 (PROVENANCE_INTEGRITY on promote)** — if (1) the fix for #33 carries `trace_id` onto `findings`, the same task_kind invariant gap propagates to `list_for_finding` (which already has no task_kind filter at trace.rs:117); the fix should bind the contract at BOTH read sites, not just patch the schema. Static pass missed it because the bug is a *future-proofing absence* — there is no current exploit, just a missing `WHERE t.task_kind = ?` clause that a future writer's invariant will rely on. Taint analysis has no signal for 'this query should filter by a column it does not currently need to'. Schema-evolution-class catch. Fix (any one + (3) closes the primitive; recommend 1+3): (1) add `AND t.task_kind = 'NovelFindings'` to the WHERE clause at trace.rs:185; pair with a `CHECK (task_kind = 'NovelFindings')` partial-index constraint on the back-link to enforce at the DB layer; (2) widen the function signature to `pub async fn list_for_candidate(&self, candidate_id: &str, task_kinds: &[&str]) -> ...` and require callers to pass an explicit allowlist — forces the read-site contract to be visible at every call; (3) add a regression test: insert a PayloadSynthesis trace (task_kind='PayloadSynthesis'), stamp it on a candidate's trace_id directly via raw SQL (bypassing the writer that doesn't currently do this), call `list_for_candidate(cand.id)`, assert `rows.is_empty()` — currently fails (returns the PS trace verbatim); (4) document the invariant on the `trace_id` field's doc-comment at candidate.rs:38-43 explicitly: 'MUST be a NovelFindings task_kind trace_id; other task_kinds are reachable via agent_traces.finding_id and must not be stamped here.'",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Verifier seed: in nyctos-core/src/store/trace.rs tests, after the existing `list_for_candidate_returns_joined_row`, add: `let ps = sample_trace_with_kind(\"trace-ps-1\", None, \"PayloadSynthesis\"); s.agent_traces().insert(&ps).await.expect(\"ps\"); let mut cand2 = sample_candidate(\"cand-ps\", \"run\", \"repo\"); cand2.trace_id = Some(\"trace-ps-1\".to_string()); s.candidate_findings().insert(&cand2).await.expect(\"cand2\"); let rows = s.agent_traces().list_for_candidate(\"cand-ps\").await.expect(\"list\"); assert!(rows.iter().all(|t| t.task_kind == \"NovelFindings\"), \"list_for_candidate must filter to NovelFindings task_kind\");` — currently fails because the PS trace is returned. Real-world consequence: if a future PR adds a per-candidate verifier-trace writer (e.g. stamping a PayloadSynthesis trace_id on a Pending candidate the moment it is dispatched to the verifier), every operator clicking the candidate's trace-viewer URL gets the PS trace's `verifier_blob` (which carries the confirmed/not-confirmed verdict) surfaced through the same UI element that previously only showed novel-discovery batch traces — a semantic widening with no migration / API-doc / UI signal."
}

