record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyctos-core/migrations/0001_v1.sql",
  "line": 120,
  "cap": "DATA_RETENTION",
  "endpoint": "DELETE /api/v1/runs/:id (and any operator-driven run purge)",
  "rationale": "`agent_traces` (migration 0001_v1.sql:120-137) declares only one FK — `FOREIGN KEY (finding_id) REFERENCES findings(id) ON DELETE SET NULL` (:136). There is NO `run_id` column on the table and NO FK from `agent_traces` to `runs`. Every other observation surface in the schema cascades on run delete (findings :62 ON DELETE CASCADE, candidate_findings — confirmed by the existing `cascade_from_run_delete` test at candidate.rs's tests module, run_findings 0004:30 ON DELETE CASCADE, chains/payloads/budgets all cascade per 0001 :86/:117/:147). `agent_traces` does not: a `DELETE FROM runs WHERE id = X` clears the run's findings → those findings' ON DELETE SET NULL fires on agent_traces.finding_id → the trace row stays alive in agent_traces with `finding_id = NULL`. NovelFindings batch traces (which migration 0005:3-15 documents as inserted with `finding_id = NULL` from the start, then reached only via `candidate_findings.trace_id`) are doubly orphaned: their candidate is cascaded away, but the candidate-side back-link is the *only* link they had. After the cascade the trace row carries `id, finding_id=NULL, task_kind, runtime_name, model, prompt_version, conversation_jsonl_path, tokens_in, tokens_out, cost_usd_micros, cache_hits, cache_misses, duration_ms, started_at, finished_at, verifier_blob` — every column except `id` and `finding_id` is *operationally* sensitive: `cost_usd_micros` is the per-call USD spend (commercial-sensitive when nyctos is run by a service provider billing customers per run), `prompt_version` reveals the prompt template the customer was on at that point in time, `conversation_jsonl_path` is a filesystem path to the raw AI prompt/response transcript (`<state>/traces/<run_id>/<task_id>.jsonl` per finding #21's anchor) — and `verifier_blob` carries dynamic-validation hints (see finding #34's analysis of what verifier_blob exposes). Three concrete failure modes drop out:\n\n(a) **GDPR right-to-erasure violation** — an operator deletes a run to honour an erasure request from the repo owner; the runs/findings/candidate cascade fires; agent_traces still carries the AI conversation transcripts (via `conversation_jsonl_path` referent on disk + tokenisation metadata on the row). The conversation transcripts themselves are not deleted from the filesystem by the run-delete path either (no `std::fs::remove_file` call near `RunStore::delete` at run.rs:190-193, just a raw DELETE FROM runs). The operator who clicked Delete sees the UI confirm 'run removed' while the most sensitive byproduct of the run — the verbatim prompt + verbatim model response that potentially contains code excerpts from the customer's repo — stays on disk under the daemon's state dir. The retention is silent: no log entry says 'traces and JSONL files retained'.\n\n(b) **commercial-sensitive cost data leaks across run-purge boundaries** — a security service running nyctos against multiple customer repos under a single daemon assumes deleting customer-X's run clears customer-X's spend record. It does not: `agent_traces.cost_usd_micros` is computable per (model, started_at) tuple, and an attacker with read access to the SQLite file (a snapshot, a leaked backup, finding #16's `ensure_bundle_path_inside_root` traversal context) can reconstruct the deleted customer's AI burn rate, model selection, and prompt iteration history (via `prompt_version` evolution over `started_at` ordering).\n\n(c) **forensic trail after compromise detection** — when a defender discovers a malicious-prompt-injection incident and triages by deleting the offending run, the audit trail of WHAT the AI returned (in `conversation_jsonl_path`'s on-disk JSONL) is preserved — which is good for forensics if the operator knew to preserve, but is unintentional: the operator's UI mental model is 'Delete = gone'. Inverse failure: an attacker who triggers a run, gets a high-value confirmed finding into the verifier output that they wish to exfiltrate via the trace, then waits for the operator to delete the offending run — the trace persists as a stable, reachable artefact (reachable via `GET /api/v1/agent_traces/:id` if such an endpoint exists, or via direct SQLite read, or via `conversation_jsonl_path` filesystem read). The 'deletion' creates a false sense of cleanup.\n\nCompounding: the `traces_for_finding` candidate-dispatch added in the uncommitted router.rs:1838 routes through `list_for_candidate` which joins through `candidate_findings.trace_id`. After the run is deleted the candidate row is gone (cascade), so the JOIN returns empty — the orphaned trace is no longer enumerable via the API but persists in the DB and filesystem. **Unreachable from the operator UI, fully readable from filesystem/SQLite.** That asymmetry is the worst of both worlds: operator cannot find the trace to verify-then-delete it, but anyone with disk access can. Distinct from finding #4 (URL-token leakage into TraceLayer logs — different artefact, different lifecycle) and finding #23 (per-run subdir permission inheritance — same JSONL family but addresses creation-time mode, not deletion-time cleanup). Static pass missed it because the bug is a *missing FK declaration* in a schema file — taint analysis has no signal for 'this table should cascade from a parent it has no column referencing', and no static rule fires on the absence of `ON DELETE CASCADE` because the table simply has no relevant column to cascade through. Schema-design review-class catch. Fix (any one + (4) closes the primitive; recommend 2+4): (1) add `run_id TEXT NOT NULL` column to `agent_traces` with `FOREIGN KEY (run_id) REFERENCES runs(id) ON DELETE CASCADE` (new migration `0006_agent_traces_run_id.sql`); backfill by joining through `findings.run_id` for traces with non-null finding_id, and through `candidate_findings.run_id` (via the trace_id back-link) for NovelFindings traces — both writers have access to `run_id` at insert time so the column is trivially populated going forward; persist in `build_trace_row` at ai_pipeline.rs's trace-construction helpers; (2) in `RunStore::delete` (run.rs:190-193), wrap the DELETE in a transaction that first selects every `agent_traces.id` reachable via findings.run_id ∪ candidate_findings (trace_id back-link), then deletes each `conversation_jsonl_path` file from disk via `std::fs::remove_file`, then DELETEs the agent_traces rows by id, then DELETEs the run; (3) at minimum, run a periodic janitor that scans for `agent_traces` rows whose `finding_id IS NULL AND id NOT IN (SELECT trace_id FROM candidate_findings WHERE trace_id IS NOT NULL)` — these are guaranteed-orphan rows — and either deletes them or surfaces a count metric the operator can monitor; (4) document the retention semantics in `docs/ai-runtime.md` explicitly: today the docs at the modified hunk (244-302) describe budget per-call cap allocation but say nothing about what happens to traces on run delete — operators reasonably assume 'delete cascades everything' from the SQLite schema's general design.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Black-box verifier seed: in nyctos-core's test harness, insert a run, insert a NovelFindings trace with finding_id=NULL, insert a candidate stamping trace_id=that-trace.id; call `s.runs().delete(\"run-1\").await.unwrap()`; assert `s.agent_traces().get(\"trace-novel-1\").await.unwrap().is_some()` — i.e. the trace SURVIVES run delete (the assertion that *exposes* the bug is the opposite of what the audit operator expects). Repeat for the static-pass class: insert a finding under run-1, insert a PayloadSynthesis trace with finding_id=finding.id, delete the run; assert the trace row STILL exists with `finding_id=NULL` (the existing test `finding_delete_sets_finding_id_null` at trace.rs:296 exercises finding-delete; the run-delete case relies on the SET NULL firing during the cascade, but the trace itself is not touched). On a real daemon: `sqlite3 <state>/db.sqlite \"SELECT count(*) FROM agent_traces WHERE finding_id IS NULL AND id NOT IN (SELECT trace_id FROM candidate_findings WHERE trace_id IS NOT NULL)\"` — non-zero rows are silently-retained orphans. Filesystem confirmation: `find <state>/traces -name '*.jsonl' -newer <run-delete-timestamp>` — JSONL files outlive their run."
}

